## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

Your code has three APIs that don't work in .NET 8:

| API | Problem in .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | Never fires (no abort = no exception) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `ProcessLoop()` loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow + cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |
| `Stop()` — Sleep + Abort | Timeout enforcement | `Join(timeout)` + token cancellation |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent to the old ThreadAbortException catch —
                // clean up partial work, then exit the loop gracefully.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel();  // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. With cooperative cancellation
            // this means GetNextItem/ProcessItem isn't checking the token.
            // Log a warning — you cannot force-kill it in .NET 8.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Critical: Make `GetNextItem` Cancellation-Aware

The old code's comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." This is the **biggest pitfall** — `CancellationToken` does **not** interrupt blocking synchronous calls. You must thread the token through:

```csharp
// ❌ Before — blocks forever, ignoring cancellation
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until item available
}

// ✅ After — wakes up when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep`, `WaitHandle.WaitOne`, or socket I/O:

| Blocking call | Cancellable replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Sleep(ms)` | `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` |
| `event.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle })` |
| Sync socket/stream read | Use async overloads with `token`, or poll with timeout |

### Key Pitfalls

1. **Cancellation isn't immediate** — it only works at checkpoints where code checks the token. If `ProcessItem()` runs for 30 seconds without checking, cancellation waits 30 seconds.

2. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — the `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one.

3. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it leaks timer handles if not disposed. The `IDisposable` pattern above handles this.

4. **`volatile bool` is no longer needed** — `CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested` is thread-safe and replaces the `_running` flag entirely.

5. **No force-kill fallback exists** — if the thread truly can't cooperate (e.g., calling unmanaged code), move that work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()`.
